Claims CLAIMS We claim: 1. A multilayer sheet, comprising a plurality of layers arranged in the following order: a first rigid layer; a first foam layer; one or more recycled material layers between the first foam layer and a second foam layer; and a second rigid layer. 2. The multilayer sheet of claim 1, further comprising outer layers adjacent to the first rigid layer and the second rigid layer 3. The multilayer sheet of claims 1 or 2, further comprising a third rigid layer adjacent to the second rigid layer. 4. The multilayer sheet of any one of claims 1-3, wherein the first rigid layer comprises: a) 25-35% HDPE,0- 20% CaCO 3 MB, 40% - 70% Talc MB and 0- 5% TiO 2 MB. 5. The multilayer sheet of any one of claims 1-4, wherein the first foam layer comprises: a) 5 - 15% LDPE, 5-20 % Talc MB, 10 - 35% recycled carton material and 25% - 55% HDPE optionally wherein the recycled material comprises recycled packaging. 6. The multilayer sheet of any one of claims 1-5, wherein the one or more recycled material layers comprise a tie layer. 7. The multilayer sheet of any one of claims 1-6, wherein each of the one or more recycled material layers comprises: a) recycled material, wherein at least a portion of the recycled material comprises recycled packaging; or 

 b) recycled material, wherein all of the recycled material comprises recycled packaging. 8. The multilayer sheet of any one of claims 1-7, wherein the second foam layer comprises: 5 - 15% LDPE, 5-20 % Talc MB, 10 - 35% recycled carton material and 25% - 55% HDPE optionally wherein the recycled material comprises recycled packaging. 9. The multilayer sheet of any one of claims 1-8, wherein the second rigid layer comprises: a) 25-35% HDPE, 0- 20% CaCO 3 MB, 40% - 70% Talc MB and 0- 5% TiCh MB. 10. The multilayer sheet of claim 2, wherein the outer layer(s) comprises: a) >50% LDPE, and/or <50% HDPE 11. The multilayer sheet of claim 3, wherein the third rigid layer comprises: a) 30% HDPE, 70% LDPE 12. The multilayer sheet of any one of claims 3-11, wherein: the first rigid layer has a thickness of 10-50 pm; the second rigid layer has a thickness of 10-50 pm; the third rigid layer has a thickness of 15-50 pm; the first foam layer has a thickness of 50-300 pm; the second foam layer has a thickness of 50-300 pm; the one or more recycled material layers each have an independently selected thickness of 2-25 pm; and/or the outer layer(s) have a thickness of 10-30 pm. 13. The multilayer sheet of any one of claims 3-11, wherein: the first rigid layer has a thickness of 37 pm; the second rigid layer has a thickness of 20 pm; the third rigid layer has a thickness of 17 pm; the first foam layer has a thickness of 200 pm; the second foam layer has a thickness of 200 pm; 

 the one or more recycled material layers each have an independently selected thickness of 5 pm; and/or outer layer(s) thickness of 15 pm. 14. The multilayer sheet of any one of claims 3-13, wherein the first foam layer and/or the second foam layer of the multilayer sheet comprises a microfoam layer produced: a) by injecting a gas in a supercritical state into the layer, or b) by chemical foaming due to a release of gas caused by an endothermic agent mixed in the layer. 15. The multilayer sheet of claim 14, wherein the gas is N2 or CO2. 16. A laminated multilayer Sheet, comprising: the multilayer sheet of any one of claims 1-15, laminated to a multilayer sheet comprising: a lamination layer, an impact resistance layer, at least one tie layer, a barrier layer, and/or at least one package sealing layer. 17. The laminated multilayer sheet of claim 16, wherein the multilayer sheet comprises a plurality of layers arranged in the following order: the lamination layer; the impact resistance layer; a first tie layer; the barrier layer; optionally, a second tie layer; a first package sealing layer; and optionally, a second package sealing layer. 18. The laminated multilayer film of claims 16 or 17, wherein the lamination layer comprises: a) 70% Dow Innate ST50 polyethylene and 25% of a blend of TiCh, slip agent and antiblock; or b) 70% metallocene linear low-density polyethylene (âmLLDPEâ), TiCh MB, slip agent and anti-block. 19. The laminated multilayer film of any one of claim 16-18, wherein the impact resistance layer comprises: a) 75% Dow Innate ST50 polyethylene and 25% LDPE. 20. The laminated multilayer sheet of any one of claim 16-19, wherein the first tie layer and/or the second tie layer each independently comprises: a) 30% Bondyram 5101 (Maleic Anhydride) or Bondyram TL 4108 (Maleic Anhydride Modified Polyethylene); and 70% Dow Innate ST50 polyethylene; or b) an mLLDPE-based maleic anhydride coextrusion tie layer blend. 21. The laminated multilayer sheet of any one of claim 16-20, wherein the barrier layer comprises: a) 100% Kuraray F171 EVOH; or b) 28-45% ethylene EVOH oxygen barrier resin or c) Grinloop, GLHP09 PE based Oxygen Barrier from AxiPolymer (Montreal, Canada) 22. The laminated multilayer sheet of any one of claim 16-21, wherein the first package sealing layer and/or the second package sealing layer each independently comprises: a) 31% Dow Innate ST50 Polyethylene, 60% Dow Engage 8770 plastomer or Dow Affinity VP 8770G1 plastomer, and 9% small adds; or b) 28-45% ethylene EVOH oxygen barrier resin. 23. The laminated multilayer sheet of any one of claims 17-22, wherein: the lamination layer has a thickness of 10-30 pm; the impact resistance layer has a thickness of 10-30 pm; the first tie layer and the second tie layer each have an independently selected thickness of 2-10 pm; the barrier layer has a thickness of 2-15 pm; and/or the first package sealing layer and the second package sealing layer each have an independently selected thickness of 10-40 pm. 24. The laminated multilayer sheet of any one of claims 17-22, wherein: the lamination layer has a thickness of 10 - 20 pm; the impact resistance layer has a thickness of 10 - 20 pm; the first tie layer and the second tie layer each have an independently selected thickness of 2 - 10 pm; the barrier layer has a thickness of 2-10 pm; and the first package sealing layer and the second package sealing layer each have an independently selected thickness of 10 - 20 pm. 25. A method for manufacturing aseptic packaging, comprising: a) providing the multilayer sheet of any one of claims 1-15, wherein the multilayer sheet has a thickness of 200-800 pm and a nominal bending stiffness of 30-500 Taber units; b) cutting one or more holes through the multilayer sheet; c) generating a laminated multilayer sheet by laminating the multilayer sheet cut in step b) to a multilayer sheet comprising a lamination layer, an impact resistance layer, at least one tie layer, a barrier layer, and at least one package sealing layer, wherein the lamination results in the one or more holes being covered by the multilayer sheet; d) generating a creased aseptic packaging by adding one or more creases to the laminated multilayer sheet; and e) optionally, winding the pre-creased aseptic packaging into a roll. 26. The method of claim 25, wherein the nominal bending stiffness is measured at 15Â°. 27. The method of claims 25 or 26, wherein the multilayer sheet provided in step a) comprises a minimum of 5, 10, 15, 20,25%, 30% or 35% recycled polyolefin. 28. The method of any one of claims 25-27, further comprising a step of: surface-treating both sides of the multilayer sheet provided in step a) to increase an energy level of a surface of the multilayer sheet to a minimum of 35 dyne while blocking out a vertical lapse seal area on the surface, prior to step b). 29. The method of any one of claims 25-28, further comprising a step of printing on at least one side of the multilayer sheet provided in step a), after surface-treating both sides of the multilayer sheet. 30. The method of claim 29, wherein the printing is: a) coated with a 2-stage laquer capable of protecting the ink from the hydrogen peroxide and add resistance to the high temperature air blowing in the aseptic chamber; and/or b) includes two sets of registration markings, one set required for the creasing operation and one set compatible with a roll-fed filling machine; optionally, wherein the ink package used for the printing is also resistant to hydrogen peroxide. 31. The method of any one of claims 25-30, wherein steps b) through d) are performed using a multiple-die rotary creasing machine, wherein a first die is configured to cut the one or more holes through the multilayer sheet, a barrier film is laminated onto a non-printed side of the multilayer film, and a second die adds the one or more creases to the laminated multilayer film. 32. The method of any one of claims 25-30, wherein steps b) through d) are performed using a multiple-die rotary creasing machine, wherein a first die is configured to insert a perforated rectangle into the rigid sheet in order to form a removable spout on one or both of the folded corners of the finished box. A barrier film is laminated onto a non-printed side of the multilayer film, and a second die adds the one or more creases to the laminated multilayer film. 33. The method of any one of claims 25-31, wherein the one or more creases added to the laminated multilayer sheet in step d) are configured to allow the laminated multilayer sheet to be folded into a rigid box. 34. A method for filling aseptic packaging, comprising: a) providing the creased aseptic packaging of any one of claims 23-30, wherein the creased aseptic packaging is wound into a roll; 

 b) sterilizing the creased aseptic packaging by feeding the roll into a roll-fed aseptic filling machine configured to sterilize the creased aseptic packaging by passing it through a heated bath containing hydrogen peroxide, optionally where the bath temperature ranges from 40-80 Â°C and the hydrogen peroxide concentration by weight is 20-50%; c) following sterilization, removing the hydrogen peroxide from the creased aseptic packaging; d) folding the creased aseptic packaging into a continuous tube and sealing the tube vertically to form a continuous, liquid-tight tube; e) filling the tube with a pasteurized liquid; and f) sealing the filed tube horizontally. 35. The method of claim 34, wherein step f) is performed by a roll-fed aseptic filling machine where induction-heated opposing jaws are configured to seal the filled tube by means of impulse heating, constant temperature heating or ultrasonic, upon closing and pull the tube simultaneously. 36. The method of claims 34 or 35, where prior to filling packages, a water ring is mounted on the exits of the aseptic chamber and used to spray a water mist on the packaging material during a filling pipe sterilization step performed prior to or during step b). 37. The method of any one of claims 34-36, wherein steps d) through f) are performed in a sterile environment.
